Boolean parameter can be useful (for DRY-ness, etc.), but to prevent any misunderstandings, I almost always introduce descriptive constants in such cases:<p><pre><code>  const bool SOMETHING = false;
  const bool OTHERTHING = true;
</code></pre>
and use them strictly for such parameter.<p>When there is a default parameter value, sometimes even only one constant can be enough (for non-default variant description).

>but I doubt Rust has something like this.<p>Oh, but it does! There&#x27;s the cond! macro:<p><pre><code>    let computed_key = cond!(
        (key.len() > self.block_size) { self.zero_pad(self.hash(key).digest) }
        (key.len() < self.block_size) { self.zero_pad(key) }
        _                             { key }
    );</code></pre>
